    {
      "name": "PHF Science Sampling",
      "type": "group",
      "isOpen": true,
      "members": [
        {
          "type": "wfs",
          "name": "Faecal Source Tracking - February 2023",
          "url": "$GEOSERVER_URL/geoserver/static_files/ows",
          "typeNames": "static_files:fecal_sampling",
          "description": "<h1>Health Assessment of Shellfish and Water</h1><h2>Te Awarua o Porirua</h2><h3>Monitoring Event 3 (ME3) February 2023</h3><strong>Ngāti Toa Rangatira, the community of Te Awarua and ESR’s He Wai Māpuna</strong><p><strong>Disclaimer:</strong></p><p><i>The work carried out in this report is from a single sampling event and therefore represents a snapshot in measurement  of contaminants from the environment that may not be representative of baseline observations. The document is not to  be assumed to be representative of the health of the environment over all the sites tested and should not be used as  such.</i></p><p>This layer presents the results of a monitoring wānanga along five historic sites significant to Ngāti Toa Rangatira  in Te Awarua o Porirua (Te Onepoto Bay, Kaiaua Bay, Paremata Railway Station, Motukaraka Point and Te Hiko Street).  This mahi is a collaborative research project that includes Ngāti Toa Rangatira, the community of Te Awarua and ESR’s  He Wai Māpuna. This third monitoring event (ME3) that builds on the first (ME1) in November 2021 and second (ME2) in  June 2022 continues a journey to understand the presence and levels of contaminants in Te Awarua o Porirua.  Understanding contaminant impacts and implications, whilst building opportunities to develop capability, and reliable  and efficient monitoring methodologies for everyone involved is key to the success of this study.</p><h4>Acknowledgements</h4><p>Kāore e ārikakira ngā mihi e rere ana ki a koutou, ko Ngāti Toa Rangatira, rātou ko ngā kaimahi o te Rūnanga me te  hapori whānui o Te Awarua. Nō mātou ko ngā kaimahi o He Waimāpuna te whiwhi ki te mahi tahi i waenganui o koutou. ‘Mā  pango, mā whero, ka oti ai te mahi.’</p><p>He Wai Māpuna would like to thank Ngāti Toa Rangatira and those that were part of the wānanga and this project. We are  grateful for the opportunity to work and wānanga together on this kaupapa for Te Awarua.</p>",
